Impact Crowdfunding Showcase: Stories & Best Practices
Dustin Moskovitz was invited
Are you interested in crowdfunding, emerging technologies, and local mission-driven projects or all of the above? You definitely won't want to miss the Impact Crowdfunding Best Practices and Showcase on Wednesday, November 12 at 6:30pm PT at Impact Hub Oakland. This groundbreaking event will showcase the stories of local social enterprises and their crowdfunding campaigns as well as convene a best practices and case studies panel. REGISTER here for FREE: http://www.eventbrite.com/e/impact-crowdfunding-showcase-best-practices-stories-tickets-13745235369 The Showcase will feature crowdfunding projects on Kickstarter, IndieGogo, and other crowdfunding platforms. The best practices panel will be moderated by Technology strategist, Entrepreneur, and Early-stage Investor, Neil Anderson. The panel will address crowdfunding best practices and case studies. The panel includes Jenny Kassan of Cutting Edge Capital, a leader in Direct Public Offerings (DPOs), Barbara Jefferson of Brave Space, and Danny Spitzberg of Peak Agency. Come enjoy stories, refreshments, music, and networking with other socially conscious people and organizations. Let's connect! Presented by Impact Hub Oakland, Generation Waking Up, and BALANCE Edutainment. PROGRAM 6:30pm – 7:00pm: Registration 7:00pm – 8:00pm: Best Practices Panel with Q&A 8.00pm – 9:00pm: Campaign Showcase and Demos 9:00pm – 9:30pm: Networking and music by DJ Uni HOST Holley Murchison is a social entrepreneur and public speaking coach based in the NYC and SF Bay Area. Her workshop series, Cool As a Cucumber: How to Master Public Speaking, prepares makers, doers and creative entrepreneurs to connect meaningfully in the moments where their voices matter most. Learn more about upcoming workshops at www.oratoryglory.com. PANEL MODERATOR Neil Anderson is a Technology Strategist, Entrepreneur and early-stage investor, with in-depth experience in Enterprise business models and impact-driven technologies, has worked in over 20 countries and has detailed knowledge of the startups hubs in San Francisco, New York and London. A Founding investor of Angel Round Capital Investment L.P., the first Angel-led venture fund in New York, Neil has also been variously an Advisor and Mentor to innovation programs for NY entrepreneurs (Entrepreneur Roundtable Accelerator), for women investors (Pipeline Fellowship), for civic innovation (Personal Democracy Forum) and for Healthcare & Hardware startup founders (Startup Leadership Program.) Neil has MA and BA degrees in Classics from Cambridge University. BEST PRACTICES PANELISTS Jenny Kassan, CEO of Cutting Edge Capital. Jenny has over nineteen years of experience as an attorney for and creator of social enterprises. She is the CEO of Cutting Edge Capital, a consulting firm that helps social ventures raise capital in alignment with their goals and values. Jenny is also an attorney at Cutting Edge Counsel, a law firm that serves social enterprise. Her legal practice areas include small business start-up and financing, securities regulation, nonprofit law, and cooperatives. Jenny earned a masters degree in City and Regional Planning from the University of California at Berkeley and earned her J.D. from Yale Law School. Danny Spitzberg, Principal at Peak Agency, a crowdfunding collective running campaigns with grassroots causes and ventures in the Bay Area. He has 6 years of experience in impact model development, community and online organizing, and campaign strategy. Danny is also a core organizer with Omni Commons (www.omnicommons.org), a collective of collectives stewarding a beautiful community center in Oakland's Temescal neighborhood. Barbara Jefferson, Brave Space - Barbara is an experience designer, facilitator, and trainer; specializing in The Work That Reconnects, leadership development, Theater of the Oppressed, and youth empowerment. As a queer person of color, B is committed to using these gifts to co-power all people, with an emphasis on queer, youth, and POC communities. Barbara has designed experiential leadership curriculum and facilitates transformative learning experiences for emerging change makers committed to social justice, sustainability, and human thriving. Barbara is passionate about creating “brave spaces” where individuals can explore their authenticity, strengthen their courage, and take steps toward holistic and community centered leadership. PROJECT SHOWCASE Generation Waking Up. Building on four years of successful youth workshops and leadership trainings, Generation Waking Up is rallying funding and support to create ReGeneration, a high school curriculum that will empower teachers to take the impact of this work directly into their classrooms. Through interactive and adaptable learning modules, students will gain an understanding of today’s global challenges and opportunities, develop 21st century leadership skills, identify their role in creating positive change, and access the tools and resources needed to make a difference at their school and in their community. Pacha's Pajamas. The award-winning story, Pacha's Pajamas, is nutritious children's entertainment that builds self-esteem, affinity to nature and encourages kids to create the world they want to live in. Pacha's magical pajamas whisk her off to imaginary worlds where she journeys with the characters on her pajamas. We are raising funds to produce the world's first interactive pajamas and their companion app and story book. Positioning the app over the pajamas and book brings the characters and their stories to life. Terra Nova. We design, build and maintain ecological landscapes and gardens in harmony with nature - the Tread Lightly service. This is fossil free landscaping at its finest. Bay Bucks. We enable businesses to purchase from other businesses that have excess inventory or extra capacity at a discount. We envision a greater Bay Area where sustainable regional economic growth and development are in service of the people and the environment, rather than corporate profits. We envision an economy that promotes stewardship of our land and local resources, supports local business and innovation, drives re-localization of production, and recreates the market from being merely transactional to a place for community building. More campaigns TBA. ARE YOU DOING A CROWDFUNDING CAMPAIGN THIS FALL? You could be featured on the main stage in the showcase! Please tell us about your crowdfunding campaign at http://bit.ly/impactcrowd. CO-SPONSORS/MEDIA PARTNERS Refreshments provided by House Kombucha, AlterEcoSF and Beanfields. Co-sponsors incude Alter Eco Foods, Sustainable Business Alliance. Media Partners Kiva Are you interested in sponsoring, donating food or drinks, or being a media partner? Please email Sylvie at sylvie@pachaspajamas.com. EVENT CONTACTS Questions? Contact the event organizers at info@balanceedutainment.com and team@generationwakingup.org. The SUB Presents "Last Thursdays: The Contours of Thought" featuring DART Collective with musical guest Brogan Bentley and James Fish
Dustin Moskovitz was invited
*this is a ticketed event and will sell out quickly. there will be no tickets at the door. purchase your tickets here: http://bit.ly/LastThursdaysTicketsJune The SUB presents "Last Thursdays", a monthly showcase of new work by visual, musical & culinary artists who inspire & expand our community. Join us on June 25th as we showcase new works by DART Collective with musical guest Brogan Bentley and James Fish. We'll have an open bar and delicious snacks for your enjoyment. DART Collective is a group of collaborating artists based in San Francisco. The artists are motivated to use art to activate space and enrich time. The collective was formed for the purpose of combining multiple techniques, in an attempt to bridge the gap between art and digital mediums. MUSIC BY— Brogan Chet Bentley "San Francisco artist Brogan Bentley is part of a new generation of music-makers unrestricted by the boundaries of genre, whose focus is on creating a spiritual experience that listeners must define for themselves. Growing up in a family of musicians in California, Bentley’s musical imprints range from jazz singers to skater soundtracks. Bentley debuted his LP The Snake this past November, an album consisting of 12 tracks of melodic storytelling using elements of smoky R&B, ethereal vocals, and ambient beats." (via SF Weekly) https://soundcloud.com/brogan-bentley James Fish "Electronic music, good people, and thoughtful experience design - these are the essential qualities that serve as the creative inspiration behind every event James touches. The music he makes and mixes is intended to move your soul and get into your head - a melodic and psychedelic twist on dance music. As an avid dancer, he feels connected to the floor whether on it, or playing for it. To him, dance music should be memorable and emotional beyond just the beat." (via Resident Advisor) https://www.soundcloud.com/jamesfish https://www.facebook.com/jamesfishmusic ——— All proceeds go towards supporting the event dress classy / get loose / celebrate creativity home is where the art is ;) ——— join our mailing list for future events here: https://www.facebook.com/theSUBsf/app_100265896690345 ———— we want to make last thursdays accessible to everyone regardless of income level. if for some reason you're unable to contribute financially please contact us and we'll figure something out!

The SUB Presents "Last Thursdays: "RIOT" featuring new paintings by Harrison Love & musical guest zéro noir
Dustin Moskovitz was invited
*this is a ticketed event, purchase here before we sell out: http://bit.ly/TicketsLastThursdaysMay ________________ The SUB presents "Last Thursdays", a monthly showcase of new work by visual, musical & culinary artists who inspire & expand our community. On May 28th we unveil new works by Harrison Love with musical guest zéro noir. We'll have an open bar provided by Muffin Street Brewery, delicious snacks, and further soundtracking from Popstack for your enjoyment. So often, art is folded into the forces that herald the coming of cultural revolution. Art has the power to effect the cultural ecosystem but the predominant atmosphere of fear that we have lived in; this and the commoditization of art as a product, has removed much of its potency and responsibility. Artists have a responsibility to act as a voice, even if our work is silent. Join us this month for the RIOT, featuring: VISUAL Harrison Love: (harrisonlove.com) MUSICAL (Curated by Earmilk) zéro noir (soundcloud.com/zeronoir) DJ in resident Popstack (soundcloud.com/popstack) COCKTAILS AND LIBATIONS Muffin Street Brewery All proceeds go towards supporting the event dress classy / get loose / celebrate creativity home is where the art is ;) —— join our mailing list for future events here: https://www.facebook.com/theSUBsf/app_100265896690345 —— *tickets here: http://bit.ly/TicketsLastThursdaysMay

STAY FRESH Wed night @ Kalliope
Dustin Moskovitz was invited
The time has arrived for us to gather on the playa for our annual breath of fresh air. But after the first few days, will you be feeling a little groggy? Need of a little mid-week pep? Or perhaps will you need to feel a little....fresh-faced? Well, come by Kalliope art car Wednesday night for a fresh start! let us energize your soul, move your feet, it'll be time to feel funky fresh. About Kalliope: an art car spectacle featuring 70,000 watts of sound, mesmerizing lights and pyrotechnics, and a collection of some seriously positive individuals behind it who want to make sure you have the most freshest Wednesday night possible. Your host, atish, has curated a lineup of DJs who will take you deep, take you dancey, and take you weird all night long... Kalliope will be cocooned by the rest of the Camp Walter fleet a collection of supersized art cars. In the spirit of radical self-inclusion, we encourage you to hop onboard any of these, have a dance, make some friends and STAY FRESH. TIME AND LOCATION: 7-10pm: [2:15 + E] (Camp Walter) - chillout beats and potluck dinner 10pm: Bus leaves camp for the DMZ, so come to get a free ride 11pm-sunrise: [10:30/11:15 + K] aka the “DMZ” - the zone where all the big art cars will park
Wednesday, September 2, 2015 at 12:00am in PDT
DMZ [10:45 + K]

Make It Funky & The Music Ninja Present: Feed Me Jack, Mosaics and The Kakaroaches
Dustin Moskovitz was invited
Make It Funky SF is teaming up with The Music Ninja, a Denver-based music discovery blog, to present a series of showcases highlighting local artists. The show should be a great night of music and the perfect introduction to the diverse tastes stemming from the partnership! Launching Saturday, February 21st, at El Rio in San Francisco, the first installment will feature: ~ Feed Me Jack ~ Experimental indie band http://feedmejack.com/ ~ Mosaics ~ Folky, electronic vibes http://wearemosaics.squarespace.com/ ~ The Kakaroaches ~ Acoustic Soul duo https://soundcloud.com/kelandia El Rio is 21+, doors open at 9PM and tickets are $5 at the door. See all you Funky Ninjas there!
Saturday, February 21, 2015 at 9:00pm - Sunday, February 22, 2015 at 1:00am in PST
3158 Mission St, San Francisco, California
